08:40.040 --> 08:48.520
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Norman Spinrad's best-known novel may be Bug
Jack Barron, a book which has stirred controversy in both England and America.

08:48.720 --> 08:56.740
It was published in this country in 1969, and it's a different sort of science
fiction novel. It's a good example of new-wave science fiction. Character and

08:56.740 --> 09:04.680
style are important, and it deals with social issues such as racism, the
establishment, drugs, the power of the media, and radical protests. There is

09:04.680 --> 09:11.520
also a good deal of sex and violence in the book, and the language is highly
colored. But Spinrad thinks the plot of the book conforms to traditional science

09:11.520 --> 09:21.000
fiction formulas. Actually, what I was trying to do in a way, the book has a
very traditional plot. As far as I was concerned, you know, it has a positive

09:21.000 --> 09:30.100
hero, it has a negative villain. The hero wins, the villain loses. All that
stuff that is considered, you know, the traditional way of plotting a book. And

09:30.100 --> 09:40.540
yet it's written in a different kind of way. It kind of takes that superficial
kind of plot and treats it in a realistic manner. The protagonist, Jack Barron,

09:40.600 --> 09:48.240
is a powerfully influential television star who has a talk show watched by 100
million people. He uses the show as a battlefield to oppose corrupt elements of

09:48.240 --> 09:55.980
society. Spinrad comments on Barron's use of power. The book is about power.

09:56.340 --> 10:07.220
It's about power itself is neutral as far as I'm concerned. It's what people do
with it that counts. Barron is a guy who likes power and keeps referring to it

10:07.220 --> 10:17.340
as a drug. And knows that he can become addicted to it. And for that reason, has
decided to stay away from it. Then he gets drawn back into playing with power

10:17.340 --> 10:26.400
because he comes to the conclusion that it's better for somebody who feels that
way about power to be wielding it than people who don't have any self

10:26.400 --> 10:36.460
-consciousness about the dangers of wielding power. So in that sense, it's a
comment on the power of the media, but it's also a comment on the morality of

10:36.460 --> 10:47.800
power, on the paradox of power, which is that if you leave power to be wielded
to be wielded by people who do not see the dangers, the personal dangers, the

10:47.800 --> 10:57.820
psychological dangers of being involved with it, then you end up with people
like Benedict Howitz, Ronald Reagan, and Richard Nixon, who do not have self

10:57.820 --> 11:06.160
-consciousness about the personal dangers, the moral dangers of chasing after
power. Whereas somebody like Barron, who is certainly an imperfect person, as

11:06.160 --> 11:19.620
all people are, at least his saving grace, if he has one, is that he is well
aware of the personal dangers of being involved in a quest for power. When

11:19.620 --> 11:26.380
Spinrad tried to get the novel published in this country, he was unsuccessful,
so he tried in Britain. But there was an outcry in Parliament against the book.

11:26.540 --> 11:35.500
He relates the story for us. That novel had a lot of trouble. It was written
under contract to Doubleday, who then rejected it. You know, you have to

11:35.500 --> 11:41.880
remember the political climate of the era. They didn't reject it. They said,
we'll publish it if you cut out all the sex, all the swear words, and all the

11:41.880 --> 11:52.980
politics, which was, you know, the whole book. So it took a long time to resell
that book here. In the meantime, I took it to Milford, to a Milford conference,

11:53.160 --> 11:59.620
and Mike Moorcock was there, and he read it, and he locked it, and he serialized
it in New World, so his first publication was actually in England, in the

11:59.620 --> 12:10.000
magazine. Now, halfway through the serialization, I forget exactly which part,
part three, part four, W. H. Smith, which was the biggest distributor, still is

12:10.000 --> 12:18.660
the biggest distributor in England, refused to distribute the magazine because
of the book in it. Now, at that time, New World had an Arts Council grant. The

12:18.660 --> 12:28.640
Arts Council was an organ of the British government. Now, the Arts Council
supported the magazine against Smith publicly, and so the flap in Parliament

12:28.640 --> 12:37.920
arose when certain right-wing members of Parliament were aghast that an organ of
the British government, the Arts Council, was defending this kind of stuff, and

12:37.920 --> 12:47.160
that's how it became a parliamentary issue. Bug Jack Barron is being made into a
movie, with a screenplay by Harlan Ellison and direction by radical filmmaker

12:47.160 --> 12:51.560
Costa Gavras. It should be interesting. More with Norman Spinrad next time.

