14:22.340 --> 14:31.320
This is Daryl Lane. And David Crews. Norman Spinrad's 1979 science fiction novel,
A World Between, signaled a change in his fiction. Spinrad's early work usually

14:31.320 --> 14:39.720
contained either subtle or overt criticism of various aspects of society. Bug
Jack Baron, The Men in the Jungle, and Agent of Chaos are good examples of this

14:39.720 --> 14:51.760
type. A World Between is also a socially oriented novel, but there's a different
element in it. Spinrad explains. I would say in general that up until, I guess,

14:51.900 --> 15:02.960
A World Between, really, a lot of my stuff was kind of critical fiction,
critical of this, critical of existing societies, critical of various things

15:02.960 --> 15:14.060
that were going on. A World Between is meant as a utopian novel, really, in any
kind of way. And it's a prescriptive kind of book. It's more of a, instead of

15:14.060 --> 15:23.060
presenting critical images of other things, the idea is to create a more
positive image of a more positive kind of future. I think if you spend enough

15:23.060 --> 15:36.320
time criticizing what exists, at some point you have some kind of moral
obligation to present something more positive and replace what you find

15:36.320 --> 15:36.620
negative.

15:41.360 --> 15:49.100
The setting for the novel is a fit one for a utopia. It takes place on the
planet Pacifica, a beautiful world of blue ocean and lush green islands that's

15:49.100 --> 15:56.540
been colonized by humans. Inhabitants of Pacifica live private lives in their
isolated islands. There are no large urban centers to cause pollution,

15:56.720 --> 16:04.120
overpopulation, or poverty. Even though they are physically isolated, the
Pacificans remain in close electronic contact with one another. They govern

16:04.120 --> 16:11.940
themselves, in fact, with a tight media web that allows them to vote immediately
on any issue of importance. But into this idyllic world comes two opposed

16:11.940 --> 16:20.460
political forces from Earth, bent on the ideological conquest of Pacifica. One
force is the Institute for Transcendental Science, a powerful organization whose

16:20.460 --> 16:32.060
goal is galactic unity under their control. They are extreme, and Spinrad says
they have two basic flaws. One is the unexamined, subtle male chauvinist bias to

16:32.060 --> 16:44.440
their culture. And the other one is the ultimate conviction that what they are
doing is the absolute most important thing in the universe, and that therefore

16:44.440 --> 17:00.020
they are morally entitled to run over other people's cultures and desires.
Absolutism, I guess, would be the, even the kind of theocratic absolutism, would

17:00.020 --> 17:08.840
be their flaw. The other force is the Femocrats, a militant women's liberation
group that is also an extreme. The struggle of these two groups for control of

17:08.840 --> 17:16.440
planets all across the galaxy is called the Pink and Blue War. It's clearly a
male-female conflict, and so far every planet the two sides have approached has

17:16.440 --> 17:25.400
ended up on one side or the other. But Pacifica is different. Spinrad's utopia
is a stable and intelligent one. The Pacificans reject both extremes and even

17:25.400 --> 17:32.780
change the minds of a few of the combatants. We asked Spinrad about reactions to
the book. How did women, for instance, respond to the Femocratic women's livers?

17:33.980 --> 17:47.840
The strange thing about the reaction to that book has been that a certain number
of men have reacted in a kind of male liberal guilt, male feminist kind of

17:47.840 --> 17:57.960
reaction against that. For the most part, women have liked the book. Women have
identified with it more than men. And actually, I even got one or two good

17:57.960 --> 18:06.800
reviews in feminist places. I think that's not quite what I expected, but that
seems to be the way it happened. I have not gotten heavy feminist flack from

18:06.800 --> 18:16.760
that. A little bit, but not much. Not much, because I think women who are
involved in feminism, or have been, or know women who are, can recognize a

18:16.760 --> 18:26.320
certain aspect of the feminist movement in the Femocrats. Whereas men who are
trying to show how liberated they are would not dream of admitting such a thing.

18:26.320 --> 18:31.560
A World Between. A different sort of book for Norman Spinrad. And we'll have
more on him tomorrow.

