20:01.960 --> 20:10.920
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. Norman Spinrad's most recent novel, Songs
from the Stars, was published by Simon & Schuster in 1980. The book describes a

20:10.920 --> 20:18.900
fragmented future society in a world devastated by nuclear war. This, of course,
is a typical Spinrad theme. But the novel also communicates the sense of wonder

20:18.900 --> 20:27.020
characteristic of good science fiction when it describes the marvels of contact
with an alien civilization. Society is split in two factions in Songs from the

20:27.020 --> 20:34.800
Stars. One faction is an Aquarian society which bans all technology, in fact
anything having to do with science, since this was what was responsible for

20:34.800 --> 20:42.280
almost destroying the Earth. And the other faction are the black scientists who
keep technology alive and maintain an illicit smuggling operation with the

20:42.280 --> 20:51.960
Aquarian society. Spinrad talks about these opposed factions. It's a book
against duality. I mean, you have two fragmented societies. They're both...

20:54.840 --> 21:05.920
Both are kind of like half-societies. So the Aquarian society there is a very
nice thing that works, except it really only works because it accepts something

21:05.920 --> 21:17.300
from the black scientists, which it doesn't want to admit that it's accepted.
And the black scientists are, again, another kind of absolutism, which

21:17.300 --> 21:20.860
doesn't...

21:20.860 --> 21:32.620
So it's a kind of a... It's a book about higher unity, I guess. As usual, with
Spinrad, the book's conflict reflects current social conditions. And then, you

21:32.620 --> 21:40.220
know, it mirrors the present thing in our society, where on the one hand you
have a great big space movement and people wanting to get into space and all the

21:40.220 --> 21:49.660
old people and all that stuff. On the other hand, you have a real atavistic neo
-Luddite movement, an anti-nuclear movement, which is really kind of willfully

21:49.660 --> 21:56.780
ignorant of a lot of things. In a way, these are the two things that could bring
about the crash.

21:59.940 --> 22:10.120
And... As well as what would survive it. So I think it's basically a book
about... The grand philosophical attempt of that book is to try and bridge the

22:10.120 --> 22:22.540
gap between science and reason and, you know, feeling, emotion, and mysticism.
And to... You know, to point to a higher unity between the two things and away

22:22.540 --> 22:31.160
from the false dichotomies and false dualisms, would seem to be really
destroying Western civilization. That's a long statement. The protagonist in the

22:31.160 --> 22:38.660
book is a laid-back Aquarian, Clear Blue Lou. Along with his girl and a
scientist, he travels up to a satellite circling the Earth. There, the three of

22:38.660 --> 22:46.560
them receive communication from some incredibly advanced alien civilizations in
another part of the galaxy. With the knowledge sent by the helpful aliens, it

22:46.560 --> 22:54.080
seems that humans will solve their own problems, unite, and start progressing
toward the stars once more. We asked Spinrad that if and when we contact an

22:54.080 --> 23:04.960
alien civilization, is it likely they will be helpful rather than hostile? As I
said in the book, I do believe that any civilization that's going to last a

23:04.960 --> 23:11.380
million years, it's going to be a million years or whatever, or even a hundred
thousand years more advanced than us, that have been around that much longer,

23:11.700 --> 23:20.640
that much more advanced science. If it's going to survive to that length of its
own history, it's got to solve it, you know, it's got to be, by that time,

23:21.880 --> 23:30.900
philosophically and emotionally pretty together or long since it destroyed
itself. I mean, we certainly will not survive a million years of our own history

23:30.900 --> 23:39.440
if it continues as it has, you know. In order that any civilization that
survives a million years of its own history has had to have gotten its

23:39.440 --> 23:53.200
political, psychological, and philosophical act together. And I don't see why,
you know. Yeah, and I do believe that if and when we run into that kind of

23:53.200 --> 24:02.760
really advanced civilizations, that they will, if not be directly actively
helpful, certainly will be benign and will not be interested in either eating us

24:02.760 --> 24:12.000
or conquering our planet or blowing us up or anything like that. Songs from the
Stars is a thoughtfully written book with a theme, but it's also good, exciting

24:12.000 --> 24:12.680
science fiction.

